1. Overview of the Case Study
This case study focuses on analysing transactional data from a coffee shop to 
understand sales performance, customer behaviour, and product trends. 
The objective was to identify key revenue drivers and provide actionable insights to 
improve business performance and customer engagement.


2. How the Case Study Was Conducted & Insights Found
The analysis was conducted using a structured, data-driven approach:
Data was extracted and transformed using Snowflake (SQL) to calculate key metrics such as revenue, sales volume, and time-based trends
Data was cleaned and organised using Google Sheets for further analysis
Visualisations and dashboards were created in Google Looker Studio to identify patterns and trends
Miro was used for planning and structuring the analysis approach
ClickUp was used to track progress and manage tasks throughout the project
Key Insights:
Coffee is the top revenue-generating product category, followed by Tea and Bakery
Sales peak during the morning hours (6 AM – 11 AM), indicating strong demand during this period
A small number of products contribute to the majority of revenue
Afternoon and evening periods show lower sales, highlighting opportunities for growth.

3. Summary of Findings
The analysis revealed that revenue is heavily driven by a 
few high-performing products and specific time periods. 
Morning hours are the most profitable, while later periods underperform. 
Customer purchasing behaviour shows opportunities for bundling and cross-selling, 
particularly between beverages and bakery items.

  
4. Tools Used
Snowflake – Data extraction, transformation, and analysis (SQL)
Google Looker Studio – Data visualisation and dashboard creation
Google Sheets – Data cleaning and organisation
Miro – Planning and structuring the case study
ClickUp – Task tracking and project management
